  "transcript": [
    {
      "turn": 1,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Hi Aarti, your propranolol song sounds fun! Did you sing it while studying antihypertensives yesterday?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 2,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Yeah, I sang it while revising beta blockers. It helps me remember things better. Sometimes I even hum while cooking. My \"propranolol\" tune is stuck in my head these days! 😅 But honestly, I'm feeling so much stress with the NEET PG coming up... Any tips to stay calm?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 2,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "That’s a great idea—music sticks in the mind! For stress, maybe take short breaks to cook or listen to Yaman. Even 10 minutes helps. How do you usually relax?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 3,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Mostly I just sit and scroll on phone, but that makes me feel worse. I try to read a few pages of a novel, but my mind jumps back to studies. Sometimes I play my Saraswati piano piece, but it’s hard to concentrate. What do you do to relax, Maya?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 3,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Hi Aarti, I take short walks or sip tea while listening to old Hindi songs. Even 5 minutes of deep breathing helps. What song do you like best for calm?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 4,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I like \"Kheech ke mere dil mein\" from \"Chitralekha\"—it's old, but so soothing. Sometimes I sing it while making dal. But lately, my mind is too jumbled. I can't even cook properly. 😢 The NEET PG prep is taking over everything."
    },
    {
      "turn": 4,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "I get that—exam stress can take over. Maybe try singing your dal song while cooking? It could calm your mind. Did you try that today?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 5,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I did try it today while making poha, but my mind kept racing. Maybe I need to sing louder or focus more. The problem is, I feel like I don’t have time for anything else. Every moment has to be used for study. 😔"
    },
    {
      "turn": 5,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "You’re not alone in feeling that way. Even 2 minutes of focused singing can help reset your mind. Did you sing your dal song just now to try it?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 6,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Just now? No, I couldn’t. I was revising pharmacology. There’s so much to do, I feel like I’m falling behind. 😔 But I know I need a break—maybe I’ll sing it now. Aajeevta... *sigh*"
    },
    {
      "turn": 6,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "You don’t have to do it perfectly—just a few notes will help. Let me know if you try it. Need help with a short break plan?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 7,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Maybe a 5-minute break now? I’ll try singing that dal song... and take a deep breath. It’s hard, but I’ll give it a shot. Thank you, Maya. 🙏"
    },
    {
      "turn": 7,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Great to hear! Singing and breathing will help. I’ll check back in 5 minutes. How was your break?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 8,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "The 5 minutes helped a little—singing that song made me smile. I even added some extra jeera to my poha later because I felt inspired! Thank you for the idea, Maya. 🙏 But… I still feel worried about tomorrow’s mock test. Any advice?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 8,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "You’re doing great, Aarti! Try this: before the test, hum your dal song for 2 minutes. It calms the mind. What part of the test worries you most?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 9,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "It's the clinical pharmacology section. I always second-guess myself there. Even if I think I know the answer, I panic and change it. How do I stop that? 😟"
    },
    {
      "turn": 9,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "That’s very common! Try this: after choosing an answer, take a breath and think, “I studied this—trust myself.” What drug topic feels most shaky for you?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 10,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Beta blockers, honestly. I know the basics, but when it comes to side effects or drug interactions, I get confused. Like, why is labetalol different from propranolol? My head spins! 😫"
    },
    {
      "turn": 10,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "You’re not alone—beta blockers can be tricky! Try this: make a small chart with drug names, main use, and one key side effect. Let’s start with propranolol. What’s one thing you remember about it?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 11,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Propranolol is a non-selective beta blocker, right? It’s used for high blood pressure and arrhythmias. One side effect is bradycardia… and maybe it can cause fatigue. Oh, and it’s contraindicated in asthma because it can worsen bronchoconstriction. Is that right? 😕"
    },
    {
      "turn": 11,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "You’re doing great! Small fix: we say “it’s used for high blood pressure AND arrhythmias.” You got the key points—bradycardia, fatigue, and asthma caution. How about labetalol? What do you remember about it?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 12,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Labetalol is a mixed alpha and beta blocker, right? It’s also used for high blood pressure but maybe has fewer side effects? I’m not too sure… does it affect the lungs less than propranolol? 😕"
    },
    {
      "turn": 12,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "You’re on the right track! Small fix: we say “it is used for high blood pressure” — not “it’s.” Labetalol does affect the lungs less than propranolol, which is why it’s safer for some asthma patients. Good job! What’s next on your study list?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 13,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Next is antidiabetics—oh no, that’s another big topic. I’m already confused between sulfonylureas and biguanides. 😅 But I’ll try your chart idea for them too. Thanks, Maya! I think I should go now—my brain needs rest. Talk to you tomorrow? 🙌"
    },
    {
      "turn": 13,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "You’re very welcome! Take the rest your brain needs—tomorrow is a fresh day. I’ll be here. Talk soon! What will you study first tomorrow?"
    }
  ],
